 cultural formations have spawned rapid and unforeseen changes in the forms, meanings, and spatial organization of sexual labor. Drawing upon dynamic and innovative research with sex workers, their clients, and state actors, Bernstein argues that in cities such as San Francisco, Stockholm, and Amstersdam, the nature of what is purchased in commercial sexual encounters is also new. Rather than the expedient exchange of cash for sexual relations, what sex workers are increasingly paid to offer their clients is an erotic experience premised upon the performance of authentic interpersonal connection. As such, contemporary sex markets are emblematic of a cultural moment in which the boundaries between intimacy and commerce—and between public life and private—have been radically redrawn. Not simply a compelling exploration of the changing landscape of sex-work, Temporarily Yours ultimately lays bare the intimate intersections of political economy, desire, and culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aProstitution. 0aSex-oriented businesses. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  asex, sexuality, commerce, authenticity, intimacy, employment, legitimacy, criminalization, criminology, prostitution, human trafficking, labor, erotics, connection, girlfriend experience, amstersdam, san francisco, stockholm, desire, political economy, vice, pleasure, demand, streetwalker, internet, sociology, sexual services, masculinity, gender, femininity, globalization, urbanism, emotions, nonfiction.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226044620423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226044620/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles